========================================================================
PART 1: FIBONACCI AND THE FIELD Q(√5)
========================================================================

F_p satisfies:  F_p = (φ^p - ψ^p) / √5  where φ,ψ = (1±√5)/2

In the number field K = Q(√5):
  - Ring of integers: Z[φ] = Z[(1+√5)/2]
  - Discriminant: Δ = 5
  - Class number: h = 1 (principal ideal domain)
  - Units: <-1, φ>  (fundamental unit is φ)

F_p = (φ^p - ψ^p)/√5 = Norm_{K/Q}(?)... not quite.
Actually: φ^p - ψ^p = √5 · F_p, so F_p = (φ^p - ψ^p)/√5.

In K: (φ^p) = (φ)^p is the principal ideal generated by φ^p.
The ideal (φ^p - ψ^p) = (√5 · F_p) = (√5) · (F_p).
Since (√5) = (5)^{1/2} is a ramified prime, this connects to
the factorization of (p) in K.

HOW (p) SPLITS IN Q(√5):
  - If (5/p) = +1 (i.e., 5 is QR mod p): (p) = P·P̄ splits
  - If (5/p) = -1 (i.e., 5 is NR mod p): (p) is inert
  - If p = 5: (p) = (√5)² ramifies

Splitting of (p) in Q(√5) and relation to F_p:
     p  (5/p)   Split type          F_p  F_p mod p p | F_p?
     2      1       splits            2          0      YES
     3     -1        inert            3          0      YES
     5      0     ramifies            8          3       no
     7     -1        inert           21          0      YES
