    31      1       splits      2178309          1       no
    37     -1        inert     39088169          0      YES
    41      1       splits    267914296          1       no
    43     -1        inert    701408733          0      YES
    47     -1        inert   4807526976          0      YES

KNOWN RESULT: p | F_p for ALL primes p.
This is the "Wall-Sun-Sun" property. More precisely:
  F_p ≡ (5/p) mod p  (Fibonacci's theorem)
  where (5/p) is the Legendre symbol.

So F_p ≡ +1 mod p when 5 is QR mod p (p splits in Q(√5))
   F_p ≡ -1 mod p when 5 is NR mod p (p is inert in Q(√5))
   F_p ≡ 0 mod p when p = 5 (ramified)


========================================================================
PART 2: THE FIBONACCI PRODUCT AS A RESULTANT
========================================================================

The product F_p = prod_{k=1}^m (1 + Q_k) where Q_k = sin²(mπk/p)/sin²(πk/p)

This can be rewritten. Let ω = e^{2πi/p}. Then:
  sin(πk/p) = (ω^{k/2} - ω^{-k/2}) / (2i)

But we need half-integer powers. Better: use ζ = e^{πi/p} = ω^{1/2}.
  sin(πk/p) = (ζ^k - ζ^{-k}) / (2i)
  sin(mπk/p) = (ζ^{mk} - ζ^{-mk}) / (2i)

So: Q_k = (ζ^{mk} - ζ^{-mk})² / (ζ^k - ζ^{-k})²

And: 1 + Q_k = [(ζ^k - ζ^{-k})² + (ζ^{mk} - ζ^{-mk})²] / (ζ^k - ζ^{-k})²

Let α = ζ^k, then ζ^{-k} = ᾱ (complex conjugate since |ζ|=1).
  (α - ᾱ)² = -(2i·sin(πk/p))² = -4sin²(πk/p)

So the NUMERATOR is:
  (α-ᾱ)² + (α^m - ᾱ^m)² = -(4sin²θ + 4sin²mθ) = -4(sin²θ + sin²mθ)

Hmm, signs get tricky. Let me just verify numerically that F_p
is the RESULTANT of two specific polynomials.

The resultant Res(f, g) = prod_{f(α)=0} g(α).

Candidate: F_p = Res(Φ_p(x), g(x)) / something, where Φ_p is cyclotomic.

  p=7, m=3: U_{m-1} = U_2 has degree 2
    prod(1 + U_{m-1}²) = 13.000000, F_p = 21
  p=11, m=5: U_{m-1} = U_4 has degree 4
    prod(1 + U_{m-1}²) = 89.000000, F_p = 144
  p=13, m=6: U_{m-1} = U_5 has degree 5
    prod(1 + U_{m-1}²) = 233.000000, F_p = 377
  p=17, m=8: U_{m-1} = U_7 has degree 7
    prod(1 + U_{m-1}²) = 1597.000000, F_p = 2584

========================================================================
PART 3: LUCAS NUMBERS AND L-FUNCTIONS
========================================================================

The LUCAS NUMBERS L_n = φ^n + ψ^n satisfy:
  L_n² - 5·F_n² = 4·(-1)^n

This is the NORM FORM for Q(√5):
  Norm(a + b√5) = a² - 5b²

So (L_n, F_n) lies on the "Pell conic" x² - 5y² = ±4.

Our transfer matrix trace: tr(T_B^m) = φ^{2m} + ψ^{2m} = L_{2m}

So the Fibonacci product F_p and the Lucas trace L_{2m} are
CONJUGATE quantities in Q(√5)!

  F_p = (φ^p - ψ^p)/√5   (imaginary part in Q(√5) basis)
  L_p = φ^p + ψ^p          (real part in Q(√5) basis)

And our key quantities are:
  H_from_0 spectral base = F_p = Im(φ^p) (up to √5 normalization)
  Transfer trace = L_{2m} = Re(φ^{2m})

Since p = 2m+1: F_p = F_{2m+1}, L_{2m} = L_{2m}
These are ADJACENT quantities in the φ-power expansion!

Pell conic: L_n² - 5·F_n² = 4·(-1)^n
  n=  0: L=         2, F=         0, L²-5F² =      4 = 4·(-1)^0 = 4
